                                                                                                               Siemens in power deal
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                          EFFICIENT REACH                                  
	Mumbai, April 30: Siemens and its parent have won a Rs 1,380-crore order from Adani Power to install a high voltage direct current (HVDC) transmission system of 2500MW capacity.        
	While the contract value for Siemens India is Rs 720 crore, it is Rs 660 crore for Siemens AG, its parent.        
	Siemens said the first phase of the project was scheduled to be commissioned in February, 2011, and the second phase in July, 2011.         
	The system will transmit power over 1,000 kilometres, from the Mundra power plant in Gujarat to Mohindergarh in Haryana.        
	Adani Power is setting up a 4,620MW thermal power plant at Mundra. Some of the power generated from this plant will be transmitted to Mohindergarh using the HVDC transmission technology.        
	Siemens will be responsible for the turnkey execution of HVDC terminal stations at Mundra and Mohindergarh.        
	The company will also undertake marine and inland transportation, civil works, installation and commissioning of the entire transmission system.        
	According to R.K Madan, CEO (power transmission) of Adani Enterprises, Adani Power  a group company  is developing power generating facilities aggregating to 6,600MW in a phased manner at Mundra and Tiroda in Maharashtra.        
	Armin Bruck, managing director of Siemens, said, This is the third HVDC order that we have bagged in India and we are extremely proud to win this order from Adani Power for transmitting bulk power from surplus area to deficit area.                                                                                                                                        
